security_findings.evidence:
UNPATCHED DmcEvtChannelClosed (channel close callback):
{
    ctx = VmbChannelGetPointer();
    ExAcquireFastMutex(ctx + 0x100);
    *(ctx + 0x18) = 0;
    ExReleaseFastMutex(ctx + 0x100);
    if (*(ctx + 0x70)) { PkpFreeDoubleMappedBuffer(*(ctx + 0x70)); *(ctx + 0x70) = 0; }
    if (*(ctx + 0x78)) { PkpFreeDoubleMappedBuffer(*(ctx + 0x78)); *(ctx + 0x78) = 0; }
    [WPP trace]
}

PATCHED DmcEvtChannelClosed replaces the two inline blocks with:
    PkUninitializeRingBuffer(ctx + 0x40);

PkUninitializeRingBuffer (sub_1c0001dd4):
{
    if (*(s + 0x30)) { PkpFreeDoubleMappedBuffer(*(s + 0x30)); *(s + 0x30) = 0; }   // s = ctx+0x40, s+0x30 = ctx+0x70
    if (*(s + 0x38)) { PkpFreeDoubleMappedBuffer(*(s + 0x38)); *(s + 0x38) = 0; }   // s+0x38 = ctx+0x78
}

PkpFreeDoubleMappedBuffer is identical in both builds (unpatched 0x1c000cff0, patched 0x1c0001c98):
    MmUnmapLockedPages(mdl->MappedSystemVa, mdl);
    mdl->ByteCount >>= 1;
    MmUnlockPages(mdl);
    IoFreeMdl(mdl);

DmcHotAddPageRange (sub_1c0005298) does NOT free these MDLs; it calls MmAddPhysicalMemory and WPP tracing only. No concurrent MDL-free path exists in either build.
